    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Hillary Rodham Clinton's rejection of political contributions from the American Muslim Alliance (front page, Oct. 27) is the most shameless form of pandering, not to mention hypocrisy, coming as it does from a person who prides herself on being a supporter of equal rights for people of all races and faiths.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Hillary Rodham Clinton's rejection of political contributions from the American Muslim Alliance (front page, Oct. 27) is the most shameless form of pandering, not to mention hypocrisy, coming as it does from a person who prides herself on being a supporter of equal rights for people of all races and faiths.</p>
        <p>It also lends credibility to the concern voiced by some Palestinians that her husband is not qualified to function as an honest broker in mediating differences among parties to the Middle East turmoil.</p>
        <p>NANCY S. DORFMAN  Belmont, Mass., Oct. 27, 2000</p>
      </block>
